electorates.name: Bean
electorates.infoText: The AEC is now conducting two-candidate preferred counts between Labor and Independent Jessie Price. Labor needs 27.1% of preferences to retain Bean but are currently attracting only 25.8%. The preference flows are being applied to the current first preference tallies to estimate a final count after preferences.

electorates.name: Bendigo
electorates.infoText: The current estimated preference count is based on the re-throw of preference currently being undertaken by  the AEC. This count is being used to project a result based on the more advanced first preference count. Labor needs 45.3% of preferences to retain Bendigo but are attracting only 43.2% at this stage.

electorates.name: Bennelong
electorates.infoText: Jerome Laxale is the sitting Labor member for Bennelong, but changes brought about by the redistribution of electoral boundaries gave Bennelong an underlying Labor majority. For this reason Bennelong was classified before the election as a marginal Liberal seat and Mr Laxale needed a swing in his favour to win the seat, a swing that he easily achieved.

electorates.name: Melbourne
electorates.infoText: Adam Bandt needs 33% of preference to retain his seat. The AEC's releases of official preference counts reveal flows of under 26% which means Labor still leads the projected two-candidate preferred count and remains with a chance of victory.

electorates.name: Menzies
electorates.infoText: Keith Wolahan is the sitting Liberal member for Menzies, but changes brought about by the redistribution of electoral boundaries gave Menzies an underlying Labor majority. For this reason Menzies was classified before the election as a marginal Labor seat and Mr Wolahan needed a swing in his favour to win the seat, a swing that did not occur. Based on preference flows seen so far, the Labor lead in Menzies will narrow but it still appears that Mr Wolahan will be defeated.
